<div id="review_3366157940" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3366157940" />
    <a title="Mrs B" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/85310540-mrs-b"><img alt="Mrs B" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3366157940?book_show_action=true">Jun 02, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mrs B" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mrs B" href="/user/show/85310540-mrs-b">Mrs B</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3366157940" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3696029377352510184">An exquisite tragedy in two parts, centred around the fortunes of the Soubeyran family, notably wily patriarch the Papet, and his unfortunate nephew Ugolin.<br/><br/>The author does an outstanding job at capturing the long-range cunning of the Papet, the pitiable covetousness of Ugolin, and the excruciating downfall of Jean de Florette. You can hardly bear to turn the page as the Provençal sun beats down and destroys Jean’s vision, inch by inch.<br/><br/>There’s plenty of human folly, and a complex exploration of t</span>
  <span id="freeText3696029377352510184" style="display:none">An exquisite tragedy in two parts, centred around the fortunes of the Soubeyran family, notably wily patriarch the Papet, and his unfortunate nephew Ugolin.<br /><br />The author does an outstanding job at capturing the long-range cunning of the Papet, the pitiable covetousness of Ugolin, and the excruciating downfall of Jean de Florette. You can hardly bear to turn the page as the Provençal sun beats down and destroys Jean’s vision, inch by inch.<br /><br />There’s plenty of human folly, and a complex exploration of the guilty conscience of a whole village, who are complicit in the Soubeyrans’ crimes. The author also writes with dark comic humour, though Ugolin’s blinking idiocy also inspires pity.<br /><br />Very moving, as are the Claude Berri films inspired by the books.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3696029377352510184" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


